'''Bluey''' (7 June 1910 – 14 November 1939) was an [[Australian Cattle Dog|Australian cattle dog]] owned by Les and Esma Hall of [[Rochester, Victoria|Rochester]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]]. According to ''[[Guinness World Records]]'', Bluey lived 29 years, 5 months and is the oldest dog ever verified.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/oldest-dog |title=Oldest dog |publisher=[[Guinness World Records]] |year=2017 |accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://ipfactly.com/oldest-living-creatures-earth/ | title=Oldest-Living Creatures on Earth: Oldest Living Dog — Bluey | publisher=IP Factly | work=An entry | date=June 6, 2015 | accessdate=December 29, 2015}}</ref> Two owners have made claims for longer-lived dogs [[Max (dog)|Max]] and Bella, but these claims have not been independently verified.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Knapton|first=Sarah|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/2707307/Oldest-dog-Bella-the-Labrador-dies-aged-101.html|title=Oldest dog Bella the Labrador dies – aged 29|publisher=Telegraph|date=2008-09-08|accessdate=2010-11-03 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1053471/The-worlds-oldest-dog-dies-age-203-canine-years.html|title=The world's oldest dog dies at the age of 203 (in canine years)|publisher=Daily Mail|date=2009-09-09|accessdate=2010-11-03 | location=London}}</ref>

Bluey's age, along with that of "Chilla," a mixed-breed ([[Labrador Retriever|Labrador]]-Australian Cattle Dog) reported to have lived to the age of 32 years and 12 days,<ref name=Bluey>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=R1suAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZNoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3926,2238929&dq=bluey+dog+oldest&hl=en ''World's oldest pooch dies'', Beaver County Times, 13 March 1984.] Retrieved 9 May 2011.</ref> prompted a study of the longevity of the Australian Cattle Dog to examine if the breed might have exceptional longevity. The 100-dog survey yielded a mean longevity of 13.41 years with a standard deviation of 2.36 years.<ref name="Pascal Lee Survey">Lee, P. (2011). Longevity of the Australian Cattle Dog: Results of a 100-Dog Survey. ACD Spotlight, Vol. 4, Issue 1, Spring 2011, 96-105. http://www.acdspotlight.com/</ref> The study concluded that while the Australian Cattle Dogs do live almost a year longer than most dogs of other breeds in the same weight class on average, the cases of Bluey and Chilla should be regarded as uncharacteristic exceptions rather than as indicators of common longevity for this entire breed.<ref name="Pascal Lee Survey" />

