{{Infobox royalty | name = Robert II of Flanders | image = Robert de flandre croisé.jpg | caption = Robert II of Flanders by [[Henri Decaisne]] | succession = [[Count of Flanders]] | reign = 1093 - 1111 | predecessor = [[Robert I, Count of Flanders|Robert I]] | successor = [[Baldwin VII, Count of Flanders|Baldwin VII]] | spouse = [[Clementia of Burgundy]] | issue = [[Baldwin VII, Count of Flanders|Baldwin VII of Flanders]] | father = [[Robert I, Count of Flanders|Robert I of Flanders]] | mother = [[Gertrude of Saxony]] | birth_date = {{circa|1065}} | death_date = 5 October 1111 (aged c. 46) | death_place = [[Meaux]], [[Kingdom of France]] }}
'''Robert II''' (c. 1065 &ndash; 5 October 1111) was [[Count of Flanders]] from 1093 to 1111. He became known as ''Robert of Jerusalem'' (''Robertus Hierosolimitanus'') or ''Robert the Crusader'' after his exploits in the [[First Crusade]].
==Early life== He was the eldest son of [[Robert I of Flanders]] and [[Gertrude of Saxony]].{{sfn|Runciman|1951|p=166}} His father, hoping to place the cadet branch (or "Baldwinite" branch) of Flanders over the county, began to associate him with his rule around 1086.{{sfn|Nicholas|2013|p=58}} From 1085 to 1091 he was regent of the county while his father was away on [[pilgrimage]] to the [[Holy Land]].{{sfn|Kostick|2008|p=257}}
==First Crusade== {{Main article|First Crusade}}
After becoming count in 1093, Robert joined the First Crusade, launched by [[Pope Urban II]] in 1095. He made his wife [[Clementia of Burgundy]] regent in Flanders,{{sfn|Runciman|1951|p=166}} and formed an [[The Army of Robert the Crusader|army]] that followed the retinue of his kinsman [[Godfrey of Bouillon]], [[Duke of Lower Lorraine]]. After reaching [[Constantinople]], the crusaders were obliged to swear an oath of fealty to [[Byzantine emperor]] [[Alexius I Comnenus]] and promise to return to the [[Byzantine Empire]] any land they might capture. Robert, whose father had already served Alexius during his pilgrimage in the 1080s, had no problem swearing this oath, but some of the other leaders did and there was some delay in leaving the city.
Robert then participated in the [[Siege of Nicaea]], after which the army was split into two groups. Robert marched with [[Stephen, Count of Blois|Stephen of Blois]], [[Bohemund I of Antioch|Bohemund of Taranto]], [[Robert Curthose]], and the Byzantine guides, one day ahead of the rest of the crusaders. This army was surrounded by the [[Seljuk Turks|Seljuk]] sultan [[Kilij Arslan I]] at the [[Battle of Dorylaeum (1097)|Battle of Dorylaeum]] on 30 June 1097.{{sfn|Runciman|1951|p=186}} The next day, the second army, led by [[Raymond IV of Toulouse]], Godfrey of Bouillon, and [[Hugh I, Count of Vermandois|Hugh of Vermandois]], arrived and broke the encirclement; the two armies joined together, with Robert and Raymond forming the centre. The Turks were defeated and the crusaders continued their march.
At the end of 1097 the crusaders arrived at [[Antioch]]. The [[Siege of Antioch]] lasted many months; in December, Robert and Bohemund briefly left the army to raid the surrounding territory for food, and on 30 December they defeated an army sent to relieve Antioch, led by [[Dukak]] of [[Damascus]]. Antioch was eventually betrayed to Bohemund by an Armenian guard, and Robert was among the first to enter the city, but only a few days later they were themselves besieged by [[Kerbogha]] of [[Mosul]]. On 28 June 1098, the crusaders marched out to meet him in battle;{{sfn|Runciman|1951|p=244-246}} Robert and Hugh of Vermandois led the first of six divisions. Kerbogha was defeated and the Muslim-held citadel finally surrendered to the crusaders. Robert, along with Bohemund, Raymond, and Godfrey, occupied the citadel, but Bohemund soon claimed the city for himself. Raymond also claimed it, but Robert supported Bohemund in this dispute.
[[File:Robert2Flandry.jpg|thumb|A 14th-century depiction of [[Robert&nbsp;II, Count of Flanders]] from a manuscript in the care of the [[National Library of the Netherlands]]]]
The dispute delayed the crusade even further. Raymond left Antioch to attack [[Ma'arrat al-Numan]], which was captured; Robert took part in this siege as well. Raymond then tried to bribe Robert and the other leaders to follow him instead of Bohemund; Robert was offered six thousand ''[[Solidus (coin)#France|sou]]s'', but each attempted bribe was ignored. Raymond continued south to Jerusalem in January, 1099, but Robert and Godfrey remained behind in Antioch until February. They rejoined Raymond's army at the [[Siege of Arqa]]. In June, Robert and [[Gaston IV of Bearn]] led the vanguard which arrived at [[Ramla]], and with [[Tancred, Prince of Galilee|Tancred of Taranto]] he led an expedition into [[Samaria]] to find wood in order to construct [[siege engine]]s for the [[Siege of Jerusalem (1099)|Siege of Jerusalem]]. When Jerusalem was captured on 15 July, Robert supported Godfrey's claim over that of Raymond, and on August 9 marched out with him to meet the [[Fatimid]] army under [[al-Afdal Shahanshah]] which was coming to relieve Jerusalem. Robert formed part of the centre wing in the ensuing [[Battle of Ascalon]], which resulted in a crusader victory. However, Godfrey and Raymond quarrelled over possession of Ascalon, and even Robert could not support Godfrey in this dispute; the city remained uncaptured, although the victory allowed for the establishment of the [[Kingdom of Jerusalem]].
At the end of August, Robert returned home with Robert Curthose and Raymond. On the way back they captured [[Latakia]], which was returned to the Byzantine emperor, as promised years before. Raymond remained there but both Roberts continued home by way of Constantinople, after declining Alexius' request to stay there in his service. Robert brought back with him a precious [[relic]], the arm of [[Saint George]], a gift from Alexius. The relic was placed in the church of [[Anchin Abbey]] in Flanders.{{sfn|Riley-Smith|2002|p=151}} After he returned, Robert built the monastery of St. Andrew in [[Betferkerke]], near [[Bruges]].{{sfn|Frankopan|2012|p=257}} Because of his crusade and the spoils he brought home, he was nicknamed Robert of Jerusalem.
==Later life==
During his absence, [[Holy Roman Emperor]] [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry IV]] had tried to seize imperial Flanders. Robert responded by supporting the revolt of the Commune of [[Cambrai]] against the emperor and his supporter, Bishop Gaulcher, and seized a number of [[castle]]s. Peace was restored in 1102 paid homage to the emperor for imperial Flanders, but after 1105, the new emperor, [[Henry V, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry V]], marched on Flanders, with the aid of [[Baldwin III, Count of Hainaut]] and an army from [[Holland]]. Robert stopped them outside of [[Douai]] and a new peace was signed, in which the emperor recognized Robert's claim to Douai and Cambrai.
In 1103 he made an alliance with King [[Henry I of England]], offering 1000 cavalry in exchange for an annual tribute of £500,{{sfn|Nicholas|2013|p=58}} but when Henry refused to pay, Robert allied with his nominal overlord, [[Louis VI of France]], and attacked [[Normandy]]. With the king diverted, [[Theobald II of Champagne|Theobald IV of Blois]] led a revolt of the French barons. Robert led an army against [[Meaux]]; during the battle he fell off his horse and was [[Trampling|trampled]] to death.{{sfn|Nicholas|1999|page=118}}
==Family== He married [[Clementia of Burgundy]], sister of [[Pope Callistus II]] and daughter of [[William I, Count of Burgundy]].{{sfn|Bouchard|1987|p=146}} They had three children, but only the oldest survived to adulthood. He succeeded Robert as [[Baldwin VII of Flanders]].
